Q. What is Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP) in Spring Framework?

AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming) is a programming paradigm that allows you to separate
cross-cutting concerns from your main business logic. Cross-cutting concerns are parts of
a program that affect multiple modules, such as logging, security, or transaction management.

Why use AOP?

It keeps your business logic clean and focused.
You can add or change cross-cutting behavior (like logging) in one place, rather than
scattering it throughout your code.

How does Spring implement AOP?

Spring uses proxies and aspects to apply additional behavior before, after, or around method
executions. You define aspects using the @Aspect annotation and advice using annotations like
@Before, @After, @Around.
Example: Logging with AOP

@Aspect
@Component
public class LoggingAspect {
    @Before("execution(* com.example.service.*.*(..))")
    public void logBefore(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
        System.out.println("Method called: " + joinPoint.getSignature());
    }
}

This logs every method call in the com.example.service package, without modifying the actual
service classes.